Architecture heritage
---------------------
The overall architecture — event-based parser, Rowan CST, Salsa
incremental database, HIR and IDE layering — follows the design of
rust-analyzer, which is distributed under MIT OR Apache-2.0.
Upstream: https://github.com/rust-analyzer/rust-analyzer

Language heritage
-----------------
BSL and the SDBL query language are part of the 1C:Enterprise platform.
The language itself, its keywords, its syntax and its semantic rules
belong to 1C as the platform author; they are not proprietary to any
third-party reimplementation.

Official references:
  * 1C query language: https://its.1c.ru/db/pubqlang
  * 1C code standards: https://its.1c.ru/db/v8std

Diagnostic rules
----------------
Code-quality diagnostics in crates/ide-diagnostics encode the 1C
code-style standards published at v8std.ru (CC0) and in the official
1C documentation. They do not implement a third party's proprietary
rule set.

Historical reference for the SDBL parser and lexer
--------------------------------------------------
Early grammar work in the following files was developed with the
bsl-parser project (https://github.com/1c-syntax/bsl-parser,
LGPL-3.0-or-later) as a reference source:

  * crates/parser/src/grammar/sdbl/
  * crates/parser/src/grammar/ (BSL grammar layer)
  * crates/lexer/src/sdbl.rs

These components are Tier B and are being replaced slice-by-slice
from official 1C documentation under a clean-room process described
in docs/legal/sdbl-clean-room-slices.md. Until that work completes,
the Tier B crates and the final binary remain under LGPL-3.0-or-later.

Bundled 1C platform data
------------------------
The file crates/bsl-platform/data/platform_data.json is a structured
extract of the 1C:Enterprise context-help archives (shcntx_ru.hbk,
shlang_ru.hbk). The contents — in particular method descriptions,
parameter documentation and code examples — are © ООО «1С-Софт» and
are NOT covered by this workspace's MIT, Apache-2.0 or LGPL-3.0
licensing. The file is bundled to allow reproducible builds of
bsl-analyzer without requiring every contributor to install
1C:Enterprise locally, and on the practical assumption that its use is
interoperability with the 1C platform rather than a standalone
documentation product. See crates/bsl-platform/data/PROVENANCE.md for
the full statement.

